Basic

cbind, rbind, apply

Gi s ta c mt bng nh th ny

C th nhp d liu theo dng

stu1 <- c(73, 75, 74, 74)
stu2 <- c(95, 94, 12, 95)
stu3 <- c(66, 67, 63, 100)

# Sau khi nhp theo dng, gp cc dng ny thnh 1 dataframe
stu <- rbind(stu1, stu2, stu3) # rbind means combine rows
colnames(stu) <- c("Test1", "Test2", "Test3", "Test4") # rename column name
stu

C th apply 1 function no vo tng dng/ct ca dataframe

# Apply function mean, to each row of stu matrix.
means <- apply(stu, 1, mean) # 1 means row, 2 means column
medians <- apply(stu, 1, median)
stu <- cbind(stu, means, medians) # merge means and medians to original dataframe with cbind
stu

quantile

x <- c(1, 4, 7, 9, 10, 14, 15, 16, 20, 21)
# Caluculate quantile 25%, 50% and 75% of vector
quantile(x, probs=c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75))

mean, variance

mean(x) # mean
var(x) # variance (n-1)
sd(x) # standard deviation (n-1)
summary(x)

correlation

Tm correlation coefficient ca 2 bin nh lng

# Using mtcars package to get data mtcars
head(mtcars, 5)
# We check the relation between mpg and wt variables
mtcars %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) +
  geom_point()

Now, run cov to check if there is correlation between 2 variables

cor(mtcars$mpg, mtcars$wt)

This indicates a negative linear relationship between the two variables.

Set seed

By gi ta c th m rng seed 1, bng vic to sample vi nhiu gi tr hn

set.seed(1)
sample(LETTERS, 7)
[1] "Y" "D" "G" "A" "B" "K" "N"

D thy, 5 gi tr u tin ca sample vn khng thay i, n ch b sung thm 2 gi tr ngu nhin vo seed ny. y chnh l ngha ca vic dng seed - m bo kh nng reproduced ca sample.

By gi ta th to 1 ci seed 2 vi tp mu khc

set.seed(2)
sample(LETTERS, 7)
[1] "U" "O" "F" "X" "H" "Q" "Z"

Sampling

Simple Random sampling

Ly ngu nhin n phn t trong tp N. Xc sut ly mi phn t l nh nhau. Vic ly mu ngu nhin nh ny ch ph hp nu tng th c tnh ng nht (homogeneous) v khi 1 mu ngu nhin mi c th i din c cho tng th (phn nh c 1 s thuc tnh ca tng th).

Stratified Sampling

Chn mu phn t l phng php ly mu trong trng hp tng th khng ng nht. C bn th nu tng th c th chia nh thnh nhng tng th con, th ta c th s dng cch ly mu ny.
V d mt s nhn t c th gip chia nhm mu l gii tnh, khu vc a l,

Systematic Sampling

Trng hp ta bit tng th, v mun tit kim chi ph (ti nguyn) ta cn chn mu t tng th 1 cch c h thng (c quy lut).

V d tng th 100 phn t, ly mu 10 phn t. Th quy lut l trong 10 phn t u tin, random 1 ci. Sau c cng 10. V d random 7, th s ly mu 7, 17, 27, , 97

Cluster Sampling

Ton b tp qun th s c chia thnh t cm hoc thnh tng phn. Sau chng ta s chn ngu nhin tng cm. Tt c cc c th trong cm s c s dng lm tp mu.

The main difference between cluster sampling and stratified sampling is that in cluster sampling, the cluster is treated as the sampling unit and analysis is done on a population of clusters

Ta s phn tch mt s ct nht inh, l violation_desc, issue_datetime, fine v issuing_agency

tickets <- tickets %>%
  select(violation_desc, issue_datetime, fine, issuing_agency)
tickets %>%
  head(5)

u tin hy bt u vi cu hi, nhng l do vi phm violation_desc l nhng l do g v tn sut cc l do. Ci no ph bin nht, t ph bin nht.

# R base | %>% is from tidyverse, we use it here just to display the result
xtabs(~tickets$violation_desc) %>% 
  head(5)

# tidyverse
tickets %>%
  group_by(violation_desc) %>%
  count() %>%
  head(5)

bit t trng ca tng loi vi phm (chim bao nhiu % trong tng s vi phm) th s dng prop.table

# R base
prop.table(
  xtabs(~tickets$violation_desc)
) %>%
  `*`(100) %>% 
  round(2) %>%
  head(5)

# tidyverse
tickets %>%
  group_by(violation_desc) %>%
  summarise(freq = n()) %>%
  mutate(prop = round(freq / sum(freq) * 100, 4)) %>%
  # ch ly t l ln hn 1%
  filter(prop > 1)

V th - Bar plot

# R base | not recommend for plotting
prop.table(
  xtabs(~tickets$violation_desc)
) %>%
  `*`(100) %>% 
  round(2) %>%
  barplot()

# tidyverse
tickets %>%
  group_by(violation_desc) %>%
  summarise(freq = n()) %>%
  mutate(prop = round(freq / sum(freq) * 100, 4)) %>%
  # ch ly t l ln hn 1%
  filter(prop > 1) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(violation_desc, freq), y = freq)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    coord_flip()

Distribution

Binom Distribution

Phn b binomial thng c dng m t nhng bin ngu nhin nh phn (xy ra vs khng xy ra)

Nu ta thc hin n php th nh phn, vi xc sut xy ra True l p.Th s ln xy ra True k vng l $np

# V d sample c n = 20 php th, pi l 0.5 l xc sut  s kin xy ra.
# Thc hin 10000 ln ci sample n kia v tnh xc sut
bino.gen(samples = 10000, n = 20, pi = 0.5)

C th thy, nu thc hin rt nhiu sample, th phn b binomial s tim cn normal vi gi tr k vng l \(np\)

Poisson Distribution

Phn phi Poisson thng c dng m t nhng bin ngu nhin ri rc, dng bin m.

V d tn sut 1 s kin xy ra trong 1 khong thi gian.

  • S lng xe t i qua 1 im trong khong thi gian xc nh (v d 30s)

  • S lng khch hng vo ca hng trong 1 khong thi gian xc nh (v d t 9h n 10h sng)

Nh vy, bin ngu nhin X phn phi Poisson vi tham s \(\lambda\), y \(\lambda\) l gi tr trung bnh.

\[ X \sim {\sf Poisson}(\lambda) \]

V d, bin ngu nhin X, c phn phi Poisson v \(\lambda\) l 3, tc l gi tr trung bnh ca n l 3.

V biu ra, th im cao nht ca phn b s xoay quanh 3

hist(rpois(100000, 5), breaks = 15, col = 'orange2')

C th tnh CDF, \(P(X < \alpha)\) bng cch

# Vi lambda l 5, mun tnh xc sut X nh hn 8 ta dng
ppois(8, 5)
[1] 0.9319064

c trng t mu phn phi chun

Ly mu ngu nhin \(n\) phn t trong tng th c phn phi Chun.

Mi quan st trong mu ny l 1 bin ngu nhin \(X_i\) c phn phi Chun vi trung bnh l \(\mu\) v phng sai \(\sigma^2\)

stat_normal

c trng t mu phn phi Poisson

poisson

Point estimation

c lng im. V d vi 1 bin ngu nhin phn phi chun vi tham s \(\mu\) v \(\sigma\), ta ly mu ngu nhin, v t mu ngu nhin N phn t ny ta c gng c lng 2 tham s trn.

C th n gin l ly k vng mu lm c lng cho \(\mu\) tng th v phng sai mu lm c lng cho \(\sigma\) tng th.

Gi nh, ta c 1 c lng im \(T\) ca 1 parameter \(\theta\)

Cc tnh cht ca Point estimation

Mean Square Error

Vi 1 phng php ly c lng im, thc hin trn nhiu sample th ta c cc c lng \(T_1\), \(T_2\), \(T_3\),

y l 1 ch s nh gi chun xc ca 1 c lng im. N l bnh phng ca sai s gia \(T\) v \(\theta\) v sau th tnh mean.

\[ \begin{aligned} MSE[T] &= E[(T - \theta)^2] \\ &= Var[T] + (E[T] - \theta)^2 \\ &= Var[T] + (Bias(T))^2 \end{aligned} \] MSE cng nh th c lng cng chnh xc.

Unbiased Estimators

C th thy 1 trong 2 thnh phn ca MSE l Bias ca T chnh l hiu ca \(E[T]\) v \(\theta\)

Unbiased Estimators l estimator T m \(E[T] = \theta\)

Sample mean \(\overline{X}\) v sample variance \(S^2\) l unbiased estimators ca population mean v population variance

Efficiency

Mt estimator tt l 1 estimator c MSE nh, v Efficiency cng l 1 cch ni v MSE nh

\[ eff[T] = \frac{1}{MSE[T]} \]

Consistency

Vi cc sample size khc nhau, ta c th to ra cc estimator khc nhau. V d, bin ngu nhin \(N(\mu, \sigma)\) ly sample N = 1.

Khi , c lng \(T_1\) c tnh t sample 1 phn t trn.

Thm 1 quan st vo sample trn, ta c sample 2 phn t, t tnh c \(T_2\), tng t th, tng s lng quan st, ta c cc \(T_n\) c lng, i vi sample c n phn t/quan st.

c lng l consistent nu n cng tng, th c lng \(T\) cng tin n/hi t v gi tr thc s \(\theta\)

Robustness

Mt ch s phn nh mc ph thuc ca estimator vo phn phi ca tng th.

Ni cch khc, trng hp m ta khng bit tng th c phn phi g, th vic estimate s kh v thiu chnh xc hn. Nn l 1 estimate m cng t ph thuc vo loi phn phi ca tng th th cng tt, cng Robust.

M rng, th ngoi phn phi, cc gi thit khc nh tnh c lp, cng c xt n trong Robustness

Cch xc nh Point estimator

C 2 phng php chnh dng tnh c lng im.

  • Method of moments: Da vo hm to moment (Moment generate function) ca phn phi.
  • MLE: Maximum likelyhood estimate

Da vo Method of moments m ta xc nh c 1 estimator ca population mean l sample mean. (v sample mean l 1st moment)

V d v MLE:

Fisher Information

Thng tin Fisher - s tm hiu thm sau khi cn thit.

Confidence Interval
